# DelftBlue Setup Guide

This file documents the DelftBlue-specific functionality deployed by this chezmoi repo.
It is rendered only when `profile = "delftblue"`.

## What This Profile Changes

- Leaves the default login shell unchanged and keeps the setup bash-first.
- Skips package-manager bootstrap and workstation-style tool installation.
- Adds DelftBlue shell helpers, Slurm helper commands, transfer helpers, and job templates.
- Installs a simple SSH host entry for `{{ .delftblue.host_alias }}` on machines where this repo manages `~/.ssh/config`.
- Supports a WezTerm remote-domain workflow on macOS so DelftBlue tabs and splits can stay remote.

Rendered defaults:

- SSH alias: `{{ .delftblue.host_alias }}`
- Login host: `{{ .delftblue.hostname }}`
- Module stack: `{{ .delftblue.module_stack }}`
- Slurm account: `{{ .delftblue.slurm_account }}`
- Default CPU partition: `{{ .delftblue.default_cpu_partition }}`
- Default GPU partition: `{{ .delftblue.default_gpu_partition }}`
{{- if .delftblue.project_storage_root }}
- Project storage root: `{{ .delftblue.project_storage_root }}`
{{- else }}
- Project storage root: not configured
{{- end }}

## Files Added By This Setup

- `~/.bashrc`
  Loads the cluster bash setup if available and defines DelftBlue shell functions.
- `~/.local/bin/db*`
  CLI helpers for accounts, jobs, interactive allocations, Julia+MPI initialization, and transfer.
- `~/.local/bin/dbdev-bootstrap`
  Bootstraps a user Spack checkout for DelftBlue-compatible dev tools.
- `~/.local/bin/dbdev-install`
  Installs the curated DelftBlue devtool set and `jjui`.
- `~/.config/delftblue/jobs/`
  Starter `sbatch` templates for Julia CPU, Julia MPI, and a small GPU smoke test.
- `~/.config/delftblue/spack/dev/spack.yaml`
  Curated Spack environment used by the DelftBlue dev shell.
- `~/.ssh/config`
  Contains `Host {{ .delftblue.host_alias }}` with `HostName {{ .delftblue.hostname }}` and `User {{ .delftblue.netid }}` when this repo also manages your local machine.
{{- if eq .chezmoi.os "darwin" }}
- `~/.wezterm.lua`
  Defines a WezTerm `SSH:{{ .delftblue.host_alias }}` domain and launcher entry for remote DelftBlue sessions on macOS.
{{- end }}

## Shell Functions

These come from `~/.bashrc` on DelftBlue.

- `dbmod-julia`
  Loads the Julia module stack:
  `module load {{ .delftblue.module_stack }} julia`
- `dbmod-julia-mpi`
  Loads the Julia + OpenMPI module stack:
  `module load {{ .delftblue.module_stack }} openmpi julia`
- `dbscratch`
  Changes directory to `/scratch/$USER`
- `dbproject`
  Changes directory to `DB_PROJECT_STORAGE_ROOT` if configured
- `dbspack`
  Sources the DelftBlue Spack environment in the current bash shell
- `dbdev [command ...]`
  Loads the curated DelftBlue dev environment in the current shell, or runs a command inside it

## Main Helper Commands

These are installed in `~/.local/bin/`.

- `dbdev-bootstrap`
  Run this on a login node.
  Clones Spack `v0.23.1`, copies the DelftBlue upstream config, and runs `spack compiler find`.
- `dbdev-install`
  Run this in a short CPU allocation started with `dbcpu`.
  Concretizes and installs the curated Spack environment, then installs `jjui` with:
  `go install github.com/idursun/jjui/cmd/jjui@latest`
- `dbacct`
  Shows your DelftBlue Slurm associations and accounts.
- `dblimits`
  Shows Slurm association limits for `{{ .delftblue.slurm_account }}`.
- `dbjobs`
  Runs `squeue --me`.
- `dbcpu [time] [cpus] [mem]`
  Starts a conservative interactive CPU allocation.
  Arguments mean: `time`, `cpus`, `mem-per-cpu`
  Default: `dbcpu 00:30:00 4 2G`
- `dbgpusmoke [time] [mem-per-cpu]`
  Starts a conservative interactive GPU allocation on `{{ .delftblue.default_gpu_partition }}`.
  Default: `dbgpusmoke 00:15:00 4G`
- `dbjulia-mpi-init <project-dir>`
  Loads `{{ .delftblue.module_stack }} openmpi julia`, instantiates the Julia project, and runs:
  `using MPIPreferences; MPIPreferences.use_system_binary()`
- `dbpush <local-path> [remote-subdir]`
  Rsyncs data to `/scratch/{{ .delftblue.netid }}` by default.
- `dbpull <remote-subpath> [local-dest]`
  Rsyncs data back from `/scratch/{{ .delftblue.netid }}`.
{{- if .delftblue.project_storage_root }}
- `dbprojectpush <local-path> [remote-subdir]`
  Rsyncs data to `{{ .delftblue.project_storage_root }}`.
- `dbprojectpull <remote-subpath> [local-dest]`
  Rsyncs data back from `{{ .delftblue.project_storage_root }}`.
{{- else }}
- `dbprojectpush` / `dbprojectpull`
  Installed but inactive until `project_storage_root` is set in chezmoi data.
{{- end }}

## Job Templates

Templates are stored in `~/.config/delftblue/jobs/`.

- `julia_cpu.sbatch`
  Single-node Julia CPU job.
  Defaults:
  - account `{{ .delftblue.slurm_account }}`
  - partition `{{ .delftblue.default_cpu_partition }}`
  - `--cpus-per-task=12`
  - `--mem=32G`
  - `--time=02:00:00`
- `julia_mpi.sbatch`
  Multi-node Julia + MPI job.
  Defaults:
  - account `{{ .delftblue.slurm_account }}`
  - partition `{{ .delftblue.default_cpu_partition }}`
  - `--nodes=2`
  - `--ntasks-per-node=8`
  - `--cpus-per-task=1`
  - `--time=01:00:00`
- `julia_gpu_smoke.sbatch`
  Minimal GPU verification job.
  Defaults:
  - account `{{ .delftblue.slurm_account }}`
  - partition `{{ .delftblue.default_gpu_partition }}`
  - `--gpus-per-node=1`
  - `--cpus-per-task=4`
  - `--time=00:15:00`

Typical usage:

```bash
cp ~/.config/delftblue/jobs/julia_cpu.sbatch myjob.sbatch
$EDITOR myjob.sbatch
sbatch myjob.sbatch
```

## Dev Environment

The DelftBlue dev shell is broader than the minimal HPC helper layer, but it is still loaded explicitly with `dbdev` instead of on every login.

Curated tools installed through the Spack environment:

- `nvim`
- `ripgrep`
- `fd`
- `fzf`
- `tmux`
- `bat`
- `jq`
- `gh`
- `jj`
- `lazygit`
- `shellcheck`
- `typst`

Additional install:

- `jjui`

Optional editor-side tools such as `delta`, `gitui`, `lua-language-server`, `stylua`,
`shfmt`, `texlab`, and `tinymist` are not part of the default DelftBlue Spack env right now.
The DelftBlue Neovim overlay disables those integrations automatically when the binaries are
missing.

Internet/GPU note:

- Compute nodes do not have outbound internet access.
- Use the login node for lightweight internet-requiring bootstrap work such as `dbdev-bootstrap`.
- Use a visual node only for GPU/CUDA-related installation or setup that requires both internet and access to a visible GPU.

## DelftBlue Neovim Overlay

The DelftBlue profile renders your Neovim config again, but with a cluster overlay.

Kept where practical:

- LazyVim base
- fzf-based navigation
- treesitter without auto-install
- explorer, git, quickfix, trouble
- Julia/Python/TOML/Markdown/YAML editing
- Julia REPL and Julia LSP support when `julia` is available
- `jj.nvim` and `jjui.nvim` only when the executables are present

Disabled on DelftBlue:

- AI integrations such as CodeCompanion, WTF, 99, and Sidekick
- Wakatime
- Markdown/browser preview plugins
- image rendering / preview plugins
- DAP stack
- local-path-only `jj-waltz.nvim`
- Lazy plugin update checking

## Recommended Workflow

1. Login with:
   `ssh {{ .delftblue.host_alias }}`
2. Bootstrap the dev layer once on the login node:
   `dbdev-bootstrap`
3. Check your account setup:
   `dbacct`
4. Start a short CPU allocation for heavier one-time installs:
   `dbcpu`
   then
   `dbdev-install`
5. Load the broader CLI/editor toolset when you want it:
   `dbdev`
6. Move to scratch for active run data:
   `dbscratch`
7. For Julia + MPI projects, initialize once inside the project:
   `dbjulia-mpi-init /path/to/project`
8. For quick exploratory work, use an interactive allocation instead of the login node:
   `dbcpu`
   or
   `dbgpusmoke`
9. For longer runs, copy a template from `~/.config/delftblue/jobs/`, edit it, and submit with `sbatch`.
10. Transfer large outputs with `dbpush` / `dbpull` and keep scratch as the default staging area.

## WezTerm On Your Mac

If this repo is also applied on your macOS machine, WezTerm is configured so DelftBlue can be used as a proper remote domain instead of a plain `ssh` command typed into a local shell.

- Use the WezTerm launcher entry `DelftBlue`, or the dedicated remote shortcuts, to start a DelftBlue session.
- Once you are in that remote WezTerm domain, normal tab and split actions stay on DelftBlue because they use `CurrentPaneDomain`.
- The remote bash prompt emits OSC 7 cwd updates, so new remote tabs and splits can usually start in the same directory.
- If you type plain `ssh {{ .delftblue.host_alias }}` inside a local pane, WezTerm still sees that pane as local, so remote tab inheritance is less reliable.

Recommended one-time SSH key setup on a trusted machine:

```bash
ssh-copy-id {{ .delftblue.host_alias }}
ssh {{ .delftblue.host_alias }}
```

With this repo managing your local `~/.ssh/config`, the `{{ .delftblue.host_alias }}` host entry is set up to use `~/.ssh/id_ed25519`, add it to your agent, and on macOS also use the system keychain.

If you log in with SSH keys and later need access to `/tudelft.net`, run:

```bash
kinit
```

## Safety Notes

- Do not run heavy compute jobs on the login node.
- Run lightweight internet-requiring bootstrap actions on the login node, not on compute nodes.
- Do one-time heavy devtool and plugin installation in a short interactive allocation such as `dbcpu`, not as casual login-shell work.
- Load modules inside interactive allocations or job scripts rather than assuming they are always active.
- Use `/scratch/$USER` for active job data and large temporary output.
{{- if .delftblue.project_storage_root }}
- Use project storage for longer-lived shared data at `{{ .delftblue.project_storage_root }}`.
{{- else }}
- Configure `project_storage_root` if you want project-storage transfer helpers and `dbproject`.
{{- end }}
- If this repo is also applied on your laptop, the SSH alias `{{ .delftblue.host_alias }}` should work with the rendered `~/.ssh/config`.
